Reviewed outside colonoscopy and pathology reports.
I have reviewed the patient's medications.
IMPRESSION
#1 Distal rectal cancer
Mr. Klassen is referred for further treatment of rectal cancer.  I shared with him Camelot Medical Center Pathology diagnosis which was new to him.  He has had no staging.  I discussed the development, staging, and treatment of rectal cancer with the patient and his son, Pqt.  We will proceed with lab work, CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis, and EUS followed by Colorectal Surgery consultation.  If T3 or N1 disease is noted, he will also be asked to meet with Medical Oncology and Radiation Oncology.  I will follow-up with the patient after his EUS for test results, and a CEA will also be requested.
#2 Progressive reflux symptoms
EGD will be requested to be performed at the time of his EUS, if this can be facilitated on his calendar.  If not, this can be considered at some time in the future with a future endoscopy.
#3 Actinic keratoses
The patient has numerous skin changes consistent with actinic keratoses, but given the extent he would benefit from a dermatologic evaluation.  The patient has been advised but declined a formal consultation at this time.  He can certainly pursue this closer to home in the future.
#4 Preoperative medical evaluation
Lab work, chest x-ray, and ECG are pending.  Once these are obtained and satisfied, the patient is okay for anesthesia.  He should take his metoprolol the morning of surgery with a sip of water.  I have requested his prior cardiology records.
Discussed with Dr. Lena Diggs, note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

