[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Klassen is a 75-year-old gentleman who presents for treatment of rectal cancer.  Mr. Klassen underwent his first colonoscopy March 16, 2010, for screening purposes, and three lesions were identified; two 3- to 4-mm polyp were removed from the distal sigmoid and rectum, tubulovillous adenoma with low-grade dysplasia on pathology.  A 3-cm flat, subtle, distal rectal polyp at the dentate was noted and biopsied, described as soft and not nodular.  Biopsies on outside pathology were indeterminate for adenocarcinoma; however, Camelot Medical Center pathology has reviewed the slides and described invasive grade 2 of 4 adenocarcinoma.  Mr. Klassen is referred for further evaluation and treatment.  He has remained asymptomatic from a lower GI standpoint with no nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, weight-loss, fever, hematochezia, melena, diarrhea, constipation, or change in bowel habits other than some increased gas production.  He has had reflux symptoms for several years, and these seem to be getting worse.  EGD has never been performed, and prior treatment with Prilosec was not felt to be of much help.  He currently is using District of Columbia, often two-to-three times a day.  His family history was negative for known colorectal neoplasia, although his sister just died within the past year of some type of abdominal cancer.
Comorbidities include a history of coronary artery disease for which he underwent double vessel bypass graft in 2008 along with a valve replacement (question mitral valve).  He has hyperlipidemia, hyperglycemia, and hypertension all of which are managed with diet and medication.  There is no history of bleeding disorders or anesthesia reactions.  He is allergic to penicillin and does not smoke.

[end section id="20103"]

